That's honestly a super cohesive story concept. It's easier to build broadly appealing (to wit, appealing to non-furries) fictional settings with anthropomorphic characters in them that aren't humanoid simulacra of /extant/ animals. With that in mind, you're better for avoiding characteristics associated with common mammals entirely. Not ironically anti-mammalposting; with respect to sci-fi, you already know you'll get by with feline characteristics, ala Star Trek or, more locally, HEL Jumper. Reptiles aren't common in everyday life outside of the tropics (I mean scouring everywhere like squirrels).
Lending that distinction to sauromorphs, which nobody has ever seen outside of a cratered laboratory by now, grants saurian characteristics the sort of exotic mystique that allures xenophiles, terratophiles, furries, and Captain Kirk-idealizing alien-lovers alike.

Depends on which story. Sometimes, it's just a name lifted from some book/movie/game/etc, that just happened to resonate with me.
